{"parentUuid":"18a6c589-7b7a-4136-bf40-bba272cf3937","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"e7af998e-fca6-4e9b-9e36-f30ba03f047c","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a8ca9dcfe95b7703a","slug":"calm-tinkering-seahorse","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EyDGZeK6zkWuYEveLr17ZD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 622\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/622](https://www.erdosproblems.com/622)\n    23→\n    24→Let $G$ be a regular graph with $2n$ vertices and degree $n+1$. Must $G$ have $\\gg 2^{2n}$\n    25→subsets that are spanned by a cycle?\n    26→\n    27→A problem of Erdős and Faudree [Er99]. Erdős writes 'it is easy to see' that\n    28→there are at least $(1/2 + o(1))2^{2n}$ sets that are NOT on a cycle.\n    29→\n    30→If the regularity condition is replaced by minimum degree $n+1$ then the answer is\n    31→no (consider $K_{n,n}$ with a spanning star in each part). Similarly this is false\n    32→with degree $n$, as $K_{n,n}$ shows.\n    33→\n    34→This has been resolved by Draganić, Keevash, and Müyesser [DKM25], who prove the\n    35→asymptotically tight result that there are at least $(1/2 + o(1))2^{2n}$ subsets\n    36→which are spanned by a cycle.\n    37→-/\n    38→\n    39→open scoped Classical\n    40→open SimpleGraph Finset\n    41→\n    42→namespace Erdos622\n    43→\n    44→/-- A subset $S$ of vertices is *spanned by a cycle* in $G$ if there exists\n    45→    a cycle in $G$ whose vertex set is exactly $S$. -/\n    46→def IsSpannedByCycle {n : ℕ} (G : SimpleGraph (Fin n)) (S : Finset (Fin n)) : Prop :=\n    47→  ∃ v ∈ S, ∃ p : G.Walk v v, p.IsCycle ∧ p.support.toFinset = S\n    48→\n    49→/-- The number of subsets of vertices spanned by a cycle in a graph on $2n$ vertices. -/\n    50→noncomputable def numCycleSpannedSubsets (n : ℕ)\n    51→    (G : SimpleGraph (Fin (2 * n))) : ℕ :=\n    52→  ((Finset.univ : Finset (Fin (2 * n))).powerset.filter (IsSpannedByCycle G)).card\n    53→\n    54→/--\n    55→**Erdős Problem 622** [Er99]:\n    56→\n    57→Let $G$ be a $(n+1)$-regular graph on $2n$ vertices. Then for any $\\varepsilon > 0$ and\n    58→sufficiently large $n$, $G$ has at least $(1/2 - \\varepsilon) \\cdot 2^{2n}$ subsets that are\n    59→spanned by a cycle.\n    60→\n    61→Proved by Draganić, Keevash, and Müyesser [DKM25].\n    62→-/\n    63→@[category research solved, AMS 5]\n    64→theorem erdos_622 :\n    65→    answer(True) ↔\n    66→    ∀ ε : ℝ, ε > 0 →\n    67→    ∃ N : ℕ, ∀ n : ℕ, n ≥ N →\n    68→    ∀ G : SimpleGraph (Fin (2 * n)),\n    69→      G.IsRegularOfDegree (n + 1) →\n    70→      (numCycleSpannedSubsets n G : ℝ) ≥ (1 / 2 - ε) * (2 : ℝ) ^ (2 * n) := by\n    71→  sorry\n    72→\n    73→end Erdos622\n    74→"}]},"uuid":"f9b51d9e-574a-4d28-b2fb-9d85142be1a1","timestamp":"2026-03-10T17:41:04.602Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"18a6c589-7b7a-4136-bf40-bba272cf3937"}
{"parentUuid":"f9b51d9e-574a-4d28-b2fb-9d85142be1a1","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"e7af998e-fca6-4e9b-9e36-f30ba03f047c","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a8ca9dcfe95b7703a","slug":"calm-tinkering-seahorse","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01QkHy1w9aPx9JwsT6Gakkbj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I found the Lean file for Erdos problem 622.\n\n## Results\n\n**File Path:** `/home/ryan/formal-conjectures/FormalConjectures/ErdosProblems/622.lean`\n\n**Contents:**\n\nThe file contains the formalization of Erdős Problem 622 in Lean 4. Here are the key components:\n\n1. **Problem Statement:** The problem asks whether a regular graph G with 2n vertices and degree n+1 must have many (>> 2^(2n)) subsets that are spanned by a cycle.\n\n2. **Key Definitions:**\n   - `IsSpannedByCycle`: A predicate defining when a subset S of vertices is spanned by a cycle\n   - `numCycleSpannedSubsets`: Counts the number of subsets spanned by a cycle in a graph\n\n3. **Main Theorem (`erdos_622`):** \n   - States that for an (n+1)-regular graph on 2n vertices and any ε > 0, there exist sufficiently large n such that G has at least (1/2 - ε) · 2^(2n) subsets spanned by a cycle\n   - Marked as solved by Draganić, Keevash, and Müyesser [DKM25]\n   - Currently has `sorry` as the proof, indicating it's a placeholder\n\nThe problem is categorized as \"research solved\" with AMS classification 5, and references the original problem at erdosproblems.com/622."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1390,"cache_read_input_tokens":18049,"output_tokens":358,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1390},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"reques